ğŸš€ Where to Start Writing Code
- Model First (Student.java)
- Define your entity class with Hibernate annotations.
- This ensures DB mapping is ready.
- DAO Layer (StudentDAO.java)
- Write methods for persistence (writeStudent) and retrieval (getAllStudents).
- Test DAO independently with a simple main() before wiring servlets.
- Hibernate Config (hibernate.cfg.xml)
- Set up DB connection, dialect, and mapping.
- Verify schema autoâ€‘creation in MySQL.
- Servlets (RegisterServlet, ViewStudentsServlet)
- Controllers that connect UI â†’ DAO.
- Add error handling to redirect to error.html.
- JSP/HTML Views (register.html, success.jsp, viewStudents.jsp, error.html)
- Build user interface.
- Ensure form actions and links match servlet mappings.
- web.xml
- Wire everything together with URL mappings.
- Set welcome file to register.html.

âœ… Summary
- Start coding with the model (Student.java) â†’ then DAO â†’ then Hibernate config â†’ then Servlets â†’ then JSP/HTML views â†’ finally wire in web.xml.
- The flow is MVC style:
- View (HTML/JSP) â†’ Controller (Servlets) â†’ Model/DAO (Hibernate + DB) â†’ back to View.
- error.html is your fallback page for exceptions.

Rushikesh, since youâ€™re building this as a Library Management System, you can repeat this same pattern for Books, Issues, Returns:
- Create entity classes (Book, Issue, etc.),
- DAO methods,
- Servlets for each action,
- JSPs for views.
